<subSubSection id="99E189DB66596E02FF7FFA70FCE9A658" pageId="3" pageNumber="552" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="D144DA5066596E02FF7FFA70FCE9A658" blockId="3.[151,1437,764,1619]" pageId="3" pageNumber="552">
<emphasis id="E38F064266596E02FF7FFA70FE84A600" bold="true" box="[199,315,1521,1547]" pageId="3" pageNumber="552">Remarks.</emphasis>
This species is similar to 
<taxonomicName id="16FBA1D366596E02FDE7FA73FC37A600" authority="Chou et Ma, 1981" authorityName="Chou et Ma" authorityYear="1981" box="[607,904,1521,1547]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Limassolla" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="552" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="kakii">
<emphasis id="E38F064266596E02FDE7FA73FD0CA600" box="[607,691,1521,1547]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="552">L. kakii</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="B56AA7A166596E02FD03FA70FC37A600" author="Chou, I. &amp; Ma, N." box="[699,904,1521,1547]" pageId="3" pageNumber="552" pagination="191" refId="ref3580" refString="Chou, I. &amp; Ma, N. (1981) On some new species and new records of Typhlocybinae from China (Homoptera: Cicadellidae), Entomotaxonomia, 3 (3), 191 ‾ 210." type="journal article" year="1981">Chou et Ma, 1981</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, but differs in having the aedeagus shaft with 3 apical processes. The new species is the second one known to dwell on persimmon trees in Asia, and it is considered as an occasional pest with sporadic occurrence in 
<collectingCountry id="A9EC9AC066596E02FD7DF9B8FCB6A658" box="[709,777,1593,1619]" name="South Korea" pageId="3" pageNumber="552">Korea</collectingCountry>
so far.
</paragraph>
